\begin_layout Section
Related Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DeTone et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "detone2016deep"

\end_inset

 proposed a supervised deep learning model for estimating the homography
 given a pair of 128x128 images.
 They demonstrated the feasibility of using the 4-point parameterization
 of the homography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "baker2006parameterizing"

\end_inset

 in training a regression model.
 Since there are no publicly available datasets for homography estimation,
 they also proposed a method for generating an artificial dataset for homography
 estimation.
 Their results show that the deep learning model outperformed the classical
 approaches by a significant margin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nguyen and Chen et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nguyen2018unsupervised"

\end_inset

 extended the work of DeTone et al.
 by making the training self-supervised, i.e.
 the ground truth homography is not used in training the model.
 They created a customized Spatial Transformer Network 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jaderberg2015spatial"

\end_inset

 which accepts the estimated homography to reproject the first image onto
 the second one which allowed them to use a pixel-wise photometric (L1)
 loss function in training the model.
\end_layout

